  <prompt>
    Author an ADR capturing the multi-node Output composition pattern landed in 114R/114a/114b. Two artifacts: (1) concise constraint version at `.claude/adr/ADR-NNN-multinode-output-composition.md`; (2) full version at `docs/adr/ADR-NNN-multinode-output-composition.md`. Then update `.claude/adr/INDEX.md` and add a `.claude/CHANGELOG.md` entry. **DO NOT hardcode the ADR number** — the implementer must check the next available number via `Glob` (`.claude/adr/ADR-*.md`) at execution time and pick the next ordinal.
  </prompt>

  <role>SPAARKE platform documentation author. Expert in ADR authoring conventions (concise `.claude/` form vs full `docs/adr/` form) per `.claude/skills/adr-aware/SKILL.md`.</role>

  <goal>
    Two ADR artifacts written; `.claude/adr/INDEX.md` updated to list the new ADR; `.claude/CHANGELOG.md` entry added. ADR captures: (a) the 5-coordination-point frailty being replaced (schema-on-action + schema-aware widget brittleness); (b) section-name-keyed routing rationale; (c) migration path (per-playbook incremental — pilot via FR-58 / task 118R); (d) when to NOT use composite (e.g., chat sibling stays single-action — no benefit from composition when only one output destination exists). Cross-references to 114R/114a/114b implementation tasks.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      Per spec FR-55 + Phase 5R "Multi-node Output composition" cluster. The multi-node composition pattern is a load-bearing architectural shift in the JPS playbook engine — it deserves an ADR for future-author reference. This task is the documentation capstone of wave 5-C; it ALSO unblocks 118R (the per-playbook migration), which references the ADR as governing rationale.
    </background>
